ws4-text/.body:
Text 
This section will help guide you through the following steps:

Normalize styles
Select fonts 
Define fonts
Style icon fonts


 CHROMEBOOKS!! 

Normalize style for cross browser consistency  
Your users will use different browsers. Help your users have a consistent browsing experience by resetting all styles.

Add the following to the top of styles.css.
 styles.css
 /* Reset */
 html, body, div, h1, h2, h3, h4, h5, h6, p, a,
 img, li, aside, footer, nav, section {
         margin: 0;
         padding: 0;
         border: 0;
         font-size: 100%;
         font: inherit;
 }



Select header and body fonts and define fallback fonts   
Different fonts help define areas. But you have to have a backup plan. Let's select fonts for our web page and define fallback fonts as a contingency.

Navigate to Google Fonts and find a font to use for headers.

Click the red + in the upper right of that font's section.

At the bottom of your page, a snackbar with the text 1 Family Selected will appear.

Find a font to use for body text and select the font using the steps outlined above. The snackbar at the bottom of the page will say 2 Families Selected.

Click on the snackbar to open to instructions on using the font. Click on @IMPORT and copy the @import statement.


Paste the @import statement after the normalizing styles in your styles.css file.

In the style declared for the body add your body text font using the CSS rules specified by Google. In the example above, Google specified font-family: 'Neuton', serif;.
 If you select a font with 2 word in the name you'll need to wrap the font name in quotation marks.

Add the font family for header text to the style you declared for all headers using Google's supplied CSS rule. Add the font to other styles if you want to override any other text, such as the text in the nav and footer. 
 Often you'll want to provide backup fonts for the page to fall back on in case it can't load the chosen font. A common fallback for sans-serif fonts might include Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif. For serif fonts it might include "Times New Roman", Times, serif as backups.
You can see the fallback fonts in action if you remove the "@import" statement for the fonts in your styles.css file, save your file, and reload the page. Notice how the font changes.


Define font styles  
Beautiful text adds final polish to websites. You will resize and decorate text to polish LadyDev Bar & Grill website.
Navigation text

The navigation text should be right aligned. In the nav style, add text-align: right;.
The navigation text in the hyperlink doesn't stand out enough. Let's make the following changes to the existing style for navigation hyperlinks:
Change the color using an a11y friendly contrasting color by setting "color" property.
Make the text bold using font-weight: bold;
Remove the hyperlink underline using text-decoration: none;
Increase text size using font-size: 1.5em;



Hero text

We need to apply a style to all the hero text. In index.html, notice a div with class="hero-text" wraps all tags for the hero text. We will target this class. 
Create a style for this class and add top padding of 125px;
Allocate 50% of the width of the background image by adding width: 50%;. 
Align text to center of the div by adding text-align: center;.


The header and paragraph text are too small. Let's increase text for each header and paragraph selectively. 
Set "font-size" to 5em for h1.
Set "font-size" to 1.5em for h2.
Set "font-size" to 1.25em for p.



Drink menu

The "Menu" text in the header tag needs to be larger. Create a style targeting this header and set font size to 3em. Add a 5px margin to give it a little space.
Each menu item needs to be a little larger. The header for each menu item has class="head". Create a style targeting this class within drinks menu and set font size to 2em.
Increase the size of each menu item description in the p tag by setting font size to 1.3em.   
We want the image for the drinks to display on the same row as the text. Add float: left; to the styles for the images. 

Small plates menu

Set font size for the enter section to 1.5em.
The "Small plates" text in the header tag needs to be 2em, centered, and spaced with 5px margin on the top and bottom, but no margin on the sides. 


Need a little help? Expand this section for guidance. 

Declare a style for the `h2` tag within `class="sidebar"`.
Add `font-size: 2em;` to set size.
Add `text-align: center;` to center.
Add `margin: 5px 0;` to space.



Style icon fonts  
Social icons are a must for any website. Let's style them so they match our website's theme.

In the footer, the copyright text needs to be a contrasting color, centered, and have a bottom margin of 15px.


Need a little help? Expand this section for guidance. 

Declare a style for the `footer p` selector.
Add `color: white;` to set color. You may have a different color in mind.
Add `text-align: center;` to center.
Add `margin-bottom: 15px;` to space.



The social icons are icon fonts. We can style these like they are text. Set the icons using the same contrasting color as the copyright. 
styles.css
 footer i {
     color: white;
 }


Give the icons space by setting top and bottom padding to 2px and left and right padding to 10px.
Center the list of icons by setting the "text-align" property in the ul styles.

Checkpoint
